The hotel room for two was clean and very basic. Sauna and swimming pool were nice. There's also a basic gym that hotel guests can use from 8 a.m. to 9 p.m.. Also all the hiking routes to the national park were very accessable.

Hotel restaurant offers breakfast and buffet lunch and dinner. The food was okay but nothing special and the buffets cost 19e which is quite expensive. Warning about the morning coffee. It was terrible.

Only great thing about this hotel is The National Park surrounding it. There was a sauna by the lakeside but hotel guests could`t use it, even though we stayed for the whole weekend it was totally booked for private events. Sauna indoors was available for two ours, exactly the same two ours that there was a dinner buffet, from 5 to 7 p.m. After that you couldn't get any food and there wasn't even restaurants near. Rooms are very modest with no facilities at all, no fridge or electric kettle etc. The staff seemed pretty bored. Wouldn't stay there again but I do recommend  hiking or trail running in Nuuksio National Park.
Quite simple hotel. Tiny Rooms. Great logation beautyful nature.

A very beautiful location and with the amazing weather! We couldn't have asked for a better wedding party.

I just walked around the pond and went into the restaurant. The place was so chill you could easily forget your troubles. It's lovely that it's fully booked every weekend of this summer and a few weekends of the next for events.

The buildings are of various age but well maintained and the rooms fully renovated just a few years ago. The fancy things are small and quite ordinary, such as the pond or small lake at which there are excellent saunas. The service is friendly, really friendly. The food is delicious and everything is made with great care and passion. Various diets can be taken into account here too. The rating is three to four stars on traditional terms. However, the cosy and warm home-like atmosphere would justify more. That can be seen also from the fact that the hotel is very often fully booked. So make your reservation early.

This is certainly the way to go for city people who want to immerse themselves in nature without a big hassle. A couple of pointers which I had been wondering about in advance but were not addressed on the website:
- This is NOT for anyone with mobility issues, or even anyone in poor physical condition. Getting to your tent involves climbing up/down a steep hillside, and you will need fairly good arm muscles to be able to lift yourself onto the hammock and from there into the tent.
- There are 6 tents, arranged in a formation (i.e. you have no say where your tent is pitched). They are close enough to see the other guests at all times, so don't expect privacy. Sound also travels very well between the tents.
- The tent is covered by a mosquito net and an optional rain cover. However, there seems to be no ventilation on the rain cover and it makes the air inside very stuffy.
- There is an indoor toilet and shower available for use about a 5-minute hike away (including climbing the afore-mentioned hillside).
- Breakfast is included (a sandwich, some natural yoghurt and a piece of fruit).
- The website mentions a "private" teepee which is in fact shared by all of the 6 tents. If you're in the tent closest to the teepee, this also means that there is frequent traffic past your tent as people go to the teepee and back for food and supplies.
- The sleeping experience is best shared by people of roughly similar body weight. If one party is much heavier than the other, the lighter party will end up sleeping "downhill" and constantly rolling towards the heavier party.

I don't mean to sound overly critical as we had a good time and enjoyed the experience. Just know what to expect!
